{{notability|Organizations|date=August 2013}} '''Slanguage''' is an exhibition space and [[artist collective]] in [[Wilmington, Los Angeles]], [[California]] founded by Mario Ybarra and Karla Diaz in 2002. Slanguage works with community artists, [[curator]]s and [[historian]]s on projects and workshops. Slanguage describes its art-making practice as a "three pronged approach" including "education, community-building, and interactive exhibitions."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slanguagestudio.com/about/|title=About » Slanguage Studio|website=slanguagestudio.com}}</ref>
Slanguage divides its space between experiments with media and ideas, and public performances and exhibitions. ''[[The New York Times]]'' cited Slanguage as an example of an "ever more important" type of exhibition space that provides a forum for work "uncongenial to an increasingly conservative art establishment" and for the work of students graduating from art schools "in numbers the commercial gallery system cannot begin to absorb."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/19/arts/art-architecture-doing-their-own-thing-making-art-together.html|title=ART/ARCHITECTURE; Doing Their Own Thing, Making Art Together|first=Holland|last=Cotter|date=7 June 2018|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>
From September through November, 2009, Slanguage was the resident artist group with [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles|The Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles]], as part of MOCA's Engagement Party program.<ref>[https://archive.is/20130818033130/http://sites.moca.org/party/2013/01/09/slanguage/ ]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e-flux.com/announcements/slanguage-at-engagement-party/|title=SLANGUAGE at Engagement Party - Announcements - e-flux|website=www.e-flux.com}}</ref> Other Slanguage projects include Sweeney Tate, a 2007 art installation at [[Tate Modern]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tate.org.uk/context-comment/video/tateshots-sweeney-tate|title=TateShots: Sweeney Tate - Tate|website=www.tate.org.uk}}</ref> and The Peacock Doesn’t See Its Own Ass/Let’s Twitch Again: Operation Bird Watching in London, for the [[Serpentine Gallery]]'s Uncertain States of America exhibition in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.serpentinegallery.org/2006/08/uncertain_states_of_america_9.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-08-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130904001948/http://www.serpentinegallery.org/2006/08/uncertain_states_of_america_9.html |archive-date=2013-09-04 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://slanguagestudio.com/projects/|title=Projects Slanguage Studio|website=slanguagestudio.com}}</ref>
