{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}} {{Use British English|date=July 2017}} {{Other people|William Allan}} {{Infobox artist | bgcolour = #EEDD82 | name = Sir William Allan | image = Sir William Allan.jpg | birth_date = 1782 | birth_place = [[Edinburgh]] | death_date = 23 Feb. 1850 (aged 67-68) | nationality = Scottish | field = Painting }}
'''Sir William Allan''' {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|RA}} (1782 &ndash; 23 February 1850) was a distinguished Scottish historical painter known for his scenes of Russian life. He became president of the [[Royal Scottish Academy]] and was made a Royal Academician.
==Life and work== [[File:Sir William Allan - Sir Walter Scott, 1771 - 1832. Novelist and poet - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|Sir Walter Scott, novelist and poet - painted by Sir William Allan]]
Allan was born in [[Edinburgh]], the son of William Allan Snr., macer, an officer of the [[Court of Session]]. He was educated at the [[Royal High School, Edinburgh|High School, Edinburgh]], under William Nicol (1744?-1797), the companion of [[Robert Burns]]. Showing an aptitude for art, he was apprenticed to a coach-painter, and studied under [[John Graham (painter)|John Graham]] at the [[Edinburgh College of Art|Trustees' Academy]], with [[David Wilkie (artist)|David Wilkie]], [[John Burnet (painter)|John Burnet]], and [[Alexander George Fraser]].{{sfn|Monkhouse|1885}}
After a few years he came to [[London]], and entered the schools of the [[Royal Academy]]. His first exhibited picture was a ''Gipsy Boy with an Ass'' (1803), in the style of [[John Opie]].
In 1805 he travelled, by ship, to [[Russia]], but was wrecked at [[Klaipėda|Memel]], where he raised funds for the remaining journey by painting portraits of the Dutch consul and others. He then proceeded overland to [[St. Petersburg]], passing through a great portion of the Russian army on its way to [[Battle of Austerlitz|Austerlitz]]. At the Russian capital he found friends, including Sir [[Alexander Crichton]], physician to the imperial family. Having learned Russian, he travelled in the interior of the country, and spent several years in the [[Ukraine]], making excursions to [[Turkey]], [[Tartary]], and elsewhere, studying the culture of [[Cossacks]], [[Circassians]], and [[Tartars]], and collecting arms and armour. In 1809 his picture ''Russian Peasants keeping their Holiday'' was exhibited at the Royal Academy.
His wish to return home in 1812 had to be postponed due to the [[French invasion of Russia]], many of the horrors of which he witnessed first-hand.{{sfn|Monkhouse|1885}} [[File:Allan, David - Bashkirs - 1814.jpg|right|thumb|250px|''Bashkirs'' (1814, [[Hermitage Museum|Hermitage]])]]
Allan was able to return to Edinburgh in 1814, and, in 1815, his picture ''Circassian Captives'' attracted notice at the Royal Academy, though it did not find a purchaser. However, Sir [[Walter Scott]], [[John Wilson (Scottish writer)|John Wilson]] (1785–1854) and his brother [[James Wilson (zoologist)|James]] (1795–1856), [[John Gibson Lockhart|John Lockhart]], and others, raised a lottery for it, with 100 subscribers at £10 10s. each, and the picture was won by [[Francis Wemyss-Charteris, 9th Earl of Wemyss]]. Allan remained in Edinburgh, and though his pictures (including ''Tartar Robbers dividing their Spoil'') did not find purchasers amongst his countrymen, some of them were bought by the [[Nicholas I of Russia|Grand Duke Nicholas]] when he visited Edinburgh. Allan afterwards painted some scenes from Scottish history suggested by the novels of Sir Walter Scott, such as ''Death of Archbishop Sharpe'' and ''Knox admonishing Mary Queen of Scots'' (exhibited in 1823 and engraved by [[John Burnet (painter)|John Burnet]]). His ''Death of the Regent Murray'' (exhibited 1825) was purchased by the [[Duke of Bedford]] for 800 guineas, and gained the artist his election as an associate of the Royal Academy.
In 1826 he was appointed master of the Trustees' School, Edinburgh, an office which he held until a few years before his death.{{sfn|Monkhouse|1885}}
[[File:Circassian Chief.jpg|thumb|''Circassian Chief'' (1843)]] Soon afterwards Allan's health gave way, and he was threatened with blindness. To recuperate he went to [[Rome]], and, after spending a winter there, proceeded to [[Naples]], [[Constantinople]], [[Asia Minor]], and [[Greece]]. In 1826 he exhibited ''Auld Robin Gray'' and in 1829 ''Prophet Jonah''. In 1830 he returned to Edinburgh, restored to health. His picture ''Slave Market, Constantinople'' was purchased by Alexander Hill, the publisher, and ''Byron in a Fisherman's Hut after swimming the Hellespont'' (exhibited 1831) by R. Nasmyth, who also bought Allan's portraits of Burns and Sir Walter Scott, which were engraved by John Burnet.{{sfn|Monkhouse|1885}}
In 1832 Allan was living at 8 Scotland Street in Edinburgh's [[New Town, Edinburgh|New Town]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digital.nls.uk/83399643|title=Edinburgh Post Office annual directory, 1832-1833|last=|first=|date=|website=National Library of Scotland|page=4|access-date=2018-02-16}}</ref>
In 1834 he visited [[Spain]] and [[Morocco]]. In 1835 he was elected a Royal Academician, and in 1838, on the death of Sir [[George Watson (painter)|George Watson]], was made president of the Royal Scottish Academy. In 1841 he went to St. Petersburg, and in the same year succeeded Wilkie as [[Painter and Limner|limner to the queen]] in Scotland, an office which was, as usual, followed (in 1842) by a knighthood.{{sfn|Monkhouse|1885}}<ref>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/20105/page/1504 London Gazette, 3 June 1842, page 1504.]</ref>
In 1843 Sir William exhibited ''Battle of Waterloo from the English side'', which was purchased by the [[Duke of Wellington]]. The next year he went again to St. Petersburg, where he painted, for the Czar, ''Peter the Great teaching his Subjects the Art of Shipbuilding''. The last large work which he finished was a second view of the battle of Waterloo, this time from the French side. It was exhibited at [[Westminster Hall]] in 1846, in competition for the decorations of the Houses of Parliament, but was unsuccessful. He visited Germany and France in 1847.{{sfn|Monkhouse|1885}}
In his final years Sir William lived at 72 Great King Street, a substantial Georgian townhouse over five storeys, in [[New Town, Edinburgh|Edinburgh's Second New Town]].<ref>Edinburgh and Leith Post Office Directory, 1849</ref> He died of [[Bronchitis]] at his Edinburgh home on 23 February 1850.<ref>Tait's Edinburgh Magazine March 1850</ref>
At the time of his death Sir William was engaged on a large picture of the [[Battle of Bannockburn]].{{sfn|Monkhouse|1885}}
He is buried in [[Dean Cemetery]] in [[Edinburgh]] against the north wall of the original cemetery backing onto the late Victorian extension.
